#### 3.53

The amount of dissolved O₂ in 1 L of fully oxygenated blood is  

\[
V_{\mathrm{O_2}} = 0.18\ \text{L (at 298 K, 1 atm)}
\]

Using the ideal‑gas law \(PV=nRT\) (with \(R = 0.082057\ \text{L·atm·K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}\)):

\[
n = \frac{PV}{RT}= \frac{(1\ \text{atm})(0.18\ \text{L})}{(0.082057\ \text{L·atm·K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1})(298\ \text{K})}
      \approx 7.4\times10^{-3}\ \text{mol}
\]

Number of O₂ molecules:

\[
N_{\mathrm{O_2}} = n N_A = (7.4\times10^{-3}\ \text{mol})(6.022\times10^{23}\ \text{mol}^{-1})
                \approx 4.4\times10^{21}\ \text{molecules}
\]

Each hemoglobin (Hb) molecule binds four O₂ molecules, so the required number of Hb molecules is

\[
N_{\text{Hb}} = \frac{N_{\mathrm{O_2}}}{4}
               \approx \frac{4.4\times10^{21}}{4}
               \approx 1.1\times10^{21}
\]

Thus, about **\(1.1 \times 10^{21}\)** hemoglobin molecules are needed to transport the O₂ in 1 L of fully oxygenated blood.

#### 1.1

The standard Gibbs energy is related to the standard enthalpy and entropy by  

\[
\Delta G^{\circ}= \Delta H^{\circ}-T\Delta S^{\circ}
\]

At the reference temperature \(T_{0}=298.15\ \text{K}\) we have  

\[
\Delta G^{\circ}_{0}=370.7\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1},\qquad 
\Delta H^{\circ}=416.3\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

Hence the standard entropy change for formation of Fe(g) is  

\[
\Delta S^{\circ}= \frac{\Delta H^{\circ}-\Delta G^{\circ}_{0}}{T_{0}}
               =\frac{416.3-370.7\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}}{298.15\ \text{K}}
               =\frac{45.6\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}}{298.15\ \text{K}}
               =0.1529\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1}
               =152.9\ \text{J mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1}
\]

Assuming \(\Delta H^{\circ}\) (and therefore \(\Delta S^{\circ}\)) remains constant up to 400 K, the Gibbs energy at \(T=400\ \text{K}\) is  

\[
\Delta G^{\circ}_{400}= \Delta H^{\circ}-T\Delta S^{\circ}
=416.3\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}-400\ \text{K}\times0.1529\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1}
\]

\[
\Delta G^{\circ}_{400}=416.3-61.2=355.1\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{355.1\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}}
\]

